---
layout: base.njk
title: Home
eleventyComputed:
  description: "{{ site.description }}"
---
<section class="hero">
  <p class="eyebrow">{{ site.tagline }}</p>
  <h1>Content, Experiments & Everyday Utilities</h1>
  <p>
    Think of Mentria as a laboratory for long-form writing, tiny single-page tools,
    and playful media experiments. Everything is static-first, progressively enhanced
    with HTMX or vanilla JS only when it truly matters.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="section-heading">Latest feed entries</h2>
  {% set latestPosts = collections.post | reverse | head(3) %}
  {% if latestPosts.length %}
  <div class="card-grid">
    {% for post in latestPosts %}
    <article class="card">
      <p class="eyebrow">{{ post.date | date("MMM d, yyyy") }}</p>
      <h3><a href="{{ post.url }}">{{ post.data.title }}</a></h3>
      <p>{{ post.data.description or post.templateContent | striptags | truncate(140, true) }}</p>
      <span>Read post →</span>
    </article>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
  {% else %}
    <p>No entries yet. Once you write your first Markdown file in <code>src/feed</code>, it will show up here.</p>
  {% endif %}
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="section-heading">Utility web tools</h2>
  {% set toolCards = tools | default([]) %}
  {% if toolCards.length %}
  <div class="card-grid">
    {% for tool in toolCards %}
    <article class="card">
      <p class="eyebrow">{{ tool.category }}</p>
      <h3><a href="/tools/{{ tool.slug }}/">{{ tool.title }}</a></h3>
      <p>{{ tool.summary }}</p>
      <span>Launch tool →</span>
    </article>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
  {% else %}
    <p>Add entries to <code>src/_data/tools.json</code> to populate this list.</p>
  {% endif %}
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="section-heading">What makes this stack simple</h2>
  <div class="card-grid">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Eleventy + Nunjucks</h3>
      <p>Write Markdown or HTML, sprinkle in shortcodes when needed, and Eleventy compiles everything into the <code>build</code> directory.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>HTMX Friendly</h3>
      <p>Enhance any page with HTMX attributes or custom scripts without committing to a heavy SPA framework.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>PWA Ready</h3>
      <p>Service worker and manifest live next to your templates, so shipping app-like experiences stays within the same workflow.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>
